What is System Design?

System Design = The process of designing how a software system works internally to handle real-world scale, performance, failures, and users.

It answers:

How will the system be structured?

How will components communicate?

How will it scale to millions of users?

How will data be stored safely?

How will failures be handled?

Simple Definition

System Design is about building a system that is scalable, reliable, secure, and efficient.

Example — Banking Application

When designing a banking system, we must decide:

How accounts are stored

How money transfer works safely

How to prevent double withdrawal

How system handles 1 lakh transactions/sec

How services communicate

How data consistency is maintained

This entire planning = System Design

Main Goals of System Design

Scalability → Handle growth (100 → 1M users)

Reliability → System should not crash

Availability → System should be up 24/7

Performance → Fast response (<200ms)

Consistency → Correct data (very important in banking)

Security → Prevent fraud / data leaks

Maintainability → Easy to update & extend

Two Types of Design
1. High-Level Design (HLD)

Big picture architecture.

Example:

API Gateway

Microservices

Database

Load Balancer

Cache

Messaging (Kafka)

Focus: System components & communication

2. Low-Level Design (LLD)

Internal logic & classes.

Example:

Account entity

Transaction service

Transfer flow

Locking mechanism

DB schema

Focus: Code-level design

System Design vs Coding
Coding	System Design
Writes logic	Designs system
Small scope	Large scale
Classes & methods	Services & architecture
Single user	Millions of users
Real-Life Example

Without Design:

Two users withdraw money simultaneously

Balance becomes negative ❌

With Proper System Design:

Locking / Transaction used

Correct balance maintained ✔

Where System Design is Used

